<section xml:id="sect-intro-rootfinding">
  <title>Introduction to Rootfinding</title>

  <p>
    In the beginning of the course, we were introduced to the problem of approximating the square root of 65 using only the four standard operations: addition, subtraction, multiplication and division.
    As we will see, another way to look at that problem is to show that if <m>f(x) = x^{2}-65</m>, then <m>p=\sqrt{65}</m> is the root, or the value of <m>p</m> such that <m>f(p)=0</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Examples are prevalent throughout applied sciences, and here's a more geometric one that is similar to problems in many Calculus classes:
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the area bounded by the <m>y</m>-axis, the line <m>y=x</m> and the line <m>y=\cos x</m> in the first quadrant.
      </p>

      <p>
        The area sought is the shaded area below:
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-def-int">
        <caption>Plot of <m>y=x</m> and <m>y=\cos x</m>. The shaded area bounded between the positive <m>y</m>-axis and the two curves in the first quadrant is shown.</caption>
        <image width="70%">
          <shortdescription>
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
            \fill[lightgray] (0,0) -- (0,1) -- (0.2,{cos(0.2 r)}) -- (0.4,{cos(0.4 r)})-- (0.6,{cos(0.6 r)})   -- (0.74,{cos(0.74 r)})   -- (0,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[->] (-1,0) -- (1.75,0) node [above right] {$x$};
            \draw[->] (0,-0.5) -- (0,1.25) node [above right] {$y$};
            \draw[<->] (-0.5,-0.5) -- (1.25,1.25);
            \draw[<->] plot[domain=-0.1:1.75] (\x,{cos(\x r)});
            \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The area is the definite integral of the difference of the two curves.
        However, the limits on the integral depend on the intersection point which means solving:
        <me>
          x= \cos x
        </me>
        or finding the root of <m>f(x) = x-\cos x</m>.
        This does not have what is called a <em>closed-form solution</em>.
        Such a solution would be a way to write the solution using other known functions.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    The next example is also a standard Calculus question.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the maximum of <m>f(x)=x\sin x</m> for <m>x \in [0,\pi]</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
      </p>

      <p>
        This means solving
        <me>
          f'(x) = \sin x + x \cos x = 0
        </me>
        which also does not have a closed form solution.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    And finally to illustrate that these rootfinding problems arise in other fields, this next example examines how objects fall toward the earth.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A model of an object falling near the earth that includes drag is that the height <m>y</m> as a function of time <m>t</m> is given by
        <men xml:id="eq-height-drag">
          \begin{aligned}y\amp= y_{0} - \frac{v_{\infty}^{2}}{g}\ln \biggl(\cosh \biggl(\frac{gt}{v_{\infty}}\biggr) \biggr)\end{aligned}
        </men>
        where <m>y_{0}</m> is the initial height of the object, <m>g</m> is the gravitation constant near the earth and
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}v_{\infty}\amp= \sqrt{\frac{2mg}{\rho C_{D} A}}\end{aligned}
        </me>
        is the terminal velocity with <m>m</m> as the mass, <m>C_{D}</m> is the drag coefficient and <m>A</m> is the cross-sectional area of the object.
      </p>

      <p>
        The time the object strikes the ground is given by the root of the function in <xref ref="eq-height-drag"/> knowing all the other parameters.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    These examples are among many in which a solution is sought, but no closed-form solution can be found.
    We will see in this chapter how to approximate the solutions.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-multiplicity">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <term>root</term> of a function <m>f(x)</m>, is a number <m>p</m> such that <m>f(p)=0</m>.
        The number <m>p</m> is also often called the <term>zero</term>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The root <m>p</m> of a function <m>f</m> has <alert>multiplicity</alert> <m>m</m> if <m>f</m> can be written in the form:
        <me>
          f(x) = (x-p)^{m} g(x)
        </me>
        where <m>\lim_{x \rightarrow p}g(x) \neq 0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Multiplicity usually pertain only to roots of polynomials as we saw in <xref ref="sect-polynomials"/>.
    For example, the polynomial: <m>f(x) = x^{3}+5x^{2}+3x-9</m> can be written as <m>f(x) = (x+3)^{2}(x-1)</m> so the root <m>-3</m> has multiplicity 2. </p>
    <p>
    However, a plot of the function <m>g(x) = 1-\cos x</m> that is in <xref ref="fig-multiplicity-2"/> shows that the root at <m>x=0</m> has characteristics of a function with multiplicity greater than 1. 
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-multiplicity-2">
        <caption>Plot of <m>y=1-\cos</m> showing the root of the function at <m>x=0</m>.</caption>
        <image width="70%">
          <shortdescription>
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
            \draw[->] (-3.25,0) -- (3.25,0) node [above right] {$x$};
            \draw[->] (0,-0.5) -- (0,2.25) node [above right] {$y$};
            \draw[<->] plot[smooth,domain=-3:3] (\x,{1-cos(\x r)});
            \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

  <p>
    The following theorem provides another tool to find the multiplicity. 
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-multiplicity">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> be a continuous function with <m>m</m> continuous derivatives on some open interval containing <m>p</m>.
        The equation <m>f(x)=0</m> has a root of multiplicity <m>m</m> at <m>x=p</m> if and only if
        <me>
          f(p)=f'(p)= \cdots = f^{(m-1)}(p) = 0, \quad \text{however $f^{(m)}(p) \neq 0$}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>


    <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>f</m> is continuous and has <m>m</m> continuous derivatives, we can use Taylor's Theorem (<xref ref="thm-taylors"/>) to write:
        <me>
          f(x) = \sum_{j=0}^{m-1}\frac{f^{(j)}(p)}{j!}(x-p)^{j} + \frac{f^{(m)}(p)}{m!}(x-p)^{m} + \frac{f^{(m+1)}(\xi(x))}{(m+1)!}(x-p)^{m+1}
        </me>
        for some <m>\xi \in [x,p]</m>.
        Since <m>f^{(j)}(p)=0</m> for <m>j=0,1,\ldots,m-1</m>, all terms in the summation formula above are zero and thus we can write
        <me>
          f(x) = \frac{f^{(m)}(p)}{m!}(x-p)^{m} + \frac{f^{(m+1)}(\xi(x))}{(m+1)!}(x-p)^{m+1}
        </me>
        factoring out a <m>(x-p)^{m}</m> term
        <me>
          f(x) = (x-p)^{m} \biggl( \frac{f^{(m)}(p)}{m!}+ (x-p) \frac{f^{(m+1)}(\xi(x))}{(m+1)!}\biggr),
        </me>
        which has a nonzero limit as <m>x \rightarrow p</m>, therefore <m>f(x)</m> has a root at <m>x=p</m> of multiplicity <m>m</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        In converse, assume that <m>f(x)</m> has a root of multiplicity <m>p</m>.
        This means that we can write
        <me>
          f(x) = (x-p)^{m} g(x).
        </me>
        with <m>g(p)\neq 0</m>.
        Obviously <m>f(p)=0</m>.
        Also if <m>f(x)</m> has <m>m</m> continuous derivatives, then <m>g(x)</m> does as well.
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}f'(x)\amp= m (x-p)^{m-1}g(x) + (x-p)^{m} g'(x) \\ f''(x)\amp= m(m-1) (x-p)^{m-2}g(x) + 2 m (x-p)^{m-1}g'(x) + (x-p)^{m} g''(x)\\ f'''(x)\amp= m(m-1)(m-2) (x-p)^{m-3}g(x) + 3 m (m-1) (x-p)^{m-2}g'(x) \\\amp\qquad + 3 m(x-p)^{m-1}g''(x) + (x-p)^{m} g'''(x) \end{aligned}
        </me>
        In general, we can write
        <me>
          f^{(j)}(x) = \sum_{i=0}^{j}k_{i} (x-p)^{m-j+i}g^{(i)}(x),
        </me>
        where <m>k_{i}</m> is a function of <m>m</m> (however the exact form it not needed).
      </p>

      <p>
        Evaluating <m>f^{(m-1)}</m> at <m>x=p</m> results in
        <me>
          f^{(m-1)}(p) = \sum_{i=0}^{m-1}k_{i} \cdot (p-p)^{i+1}g^{(i)}(p) = 0
        </me>
        since <m>(p-p)^{i}=0</m> for <m>i=0,1,2,\ldots,m-1</m> and evaluating <m>f^{(m)}(x)</m> at <m>x=p</m> results in
        <me>
          f^{(m)}(p) = \sum_{i=0}^{m} k_{i} (p-p)^{i} g^{(i)}(p) = k_{0} g^{(0)}(p) \neq 0
        </me>
        since <m>g^{(0)}(p)=g(p) \neq 0</m>.
        Therefore the theorem holds.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    This is quite a helpful theorem as we will see below, but to get some idea of using it in a general sense, the following shows how to find the multiplicity of roots of two particular functions.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use the above theorem to find the multiplicity of the following functions at the given root:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)= x^{4}-8x^{3}+24x^{2}-32x+16</m> at <m>p=2</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>g(x)=\sin x -\tan x</m> at <m>p=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        For the first function, differentiate and plug in <m>x=2</m> until the result is not zero.
        First, <m>f(2)=0</m>, then
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}f'(x)\amp= 4x^{3} - 24x^{2} + 48 x -32\amp f'(2)\amp= 0 \\ f''(x)\amp= 12x^{2}-48x +48\amp f''(2)\amp= 0 \\ f'''(x)\amp= 24x - 48\amp f'''(2)\amp= 0 \\ f^{(4)}(x)\amp=24\amp f^{(4)}(2)\amp= 24\end{aligned}
        </me>
        and therefore the multiplicity of the root at <m>p=2</m> is 4.
      </p>

      <p>
        For the second function <m>g(0)=0</m> and then
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}g'(x)\amp= \cos x - \sec^{2} x\amp g'(0)\amp= 0 \\ g''(x)\amp= \sin x - 2 \sec x \sec x \tan x\amp g''(0)\amp= 0 \\ g'''(x)\amp= \cos x - 4 \sec^{3} x \tan^{2} x - 2 \sec^{4} x\amp g'''(0)\amp= -1\end{aligned}
        </me>
        and therefore the multiplicity of <m>g</m> at <m>p=0</m> is 3.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</section>